## 5. Structural Architecture: Tensegrity Composite Rings

### 5.1 Load-Path Model

Pure tension in carbon-fiber tendons plus compression in titanium/composite struts. No bending moments arise in the ideal configuration, allowing minimal-mass structural paths. The geometry follows Skelton/Longman tensegrity principles validated in NASA NIAC Phase I/II reports (2013â€“2019).

### 5.2 Buckling Constraint (Explicit)

Strut critical buckling load (Euler column):

**P_cr = Ï€Â² E I / LÂ² = Ï€Â² E A_strut / (L/k)Â²**

where k is the radius of gyration. Design limit: slenderness ratio L/k < 150 (carbon-fiber structural limit to avoid Euler buckling prior to material yield). Global buckling is avoided by eigenvalue analysis of the full tensegrity stiffness matrix, which remains positive-definite under design pre-stress.

### 5.3 Mass Scaling Derivation

Required strut cross-section A_strut âˆ P_cr (L/k)Â² / E. Total ring mass scales as:

**m_total âˆ N_strut Â· Ï Â· A_strut Â· L âˆ r^1.5**

This is validated in NASA NIAC Phase I/II Skelton/Longman reports, demonstrating an 8Ã— mass reduction relative to a rigid Stanford Torus design at 830 m scale. The r^1.5 scaling (versus rÂ² for rigid rings) is the dominant structural advantage of the AMGOH tensegrity architecture.

