## 8. Human Factors & Vestibular Safety

### 8.1 Gravity Gradient (Explicit)

Head-to-foot gravity gradient across human height h:

**Î”g/g = h / r**

For the outer ring (râ‚ƒ = 56 m, h = 1.8 m):

**Î”g/g = 1.8 / 56 = 3.21%**

This is well below the 6% comfort threshold established by the NASA/ESA vestibular envelope (Hall 1997, Globus 2017). Head-to-foot differential shear is less than 0.03 g â€” imperceptible after standard 30-day adaptation protocols, supported by ISS centrifuge analog data.

### 8.2 Rotation Rate

All rings operate at Ï‰ < 4 RPM. At this rate, Coriolis forces during normal crew movement are within the human vestibular adaptation threshold. The 4 RPM constraint drives the minimum radii for each ring (râ‚ = 9 m, râ‚‚ = 21 m, râ‚ƒ = 56 m) â€” these are not arbitrary but are derived directly from this constraint.

### 8.3 Transitional Safety

Gravity transitions between rings are rate-limited to Ï‰Ì‡ â‰¤ 0.005 rad/sÂ², producing a Coriolis ramp of less than 0.05 g/s â€” below vertigo onset for any expected crew maneuver.

