### A.8 Lyapunov Stability â€” Complete Proof

**Theorem (UUB):** Under the PID control law with gains from Â§A.7, the closed-loop system áº‹ = A_cl x + E Ï„_dist with â€–Ï„_distâ€– â‰¤ Ï„Ì„ = 15 Nm is Uniformly Ultimately Bounded. All trajectories enter and remain in the set:

**Î© = { x : â€–xâ€– â‰¤ r* }**, where **r* = 2Î»_max(P) Ï„Ì„ / Î»_min(Q)**

**Proof:**

**Step 1 â€” Lyapunov function.** Choose V(x) = Â½ xáµ€ P x where P > 0 is the unique symmetric positive-definite solution of the Lyapunov equation:

**A_cl^T P + P A_cl = âˆ’Q**

for any chosen Q > 0. Existence is guaranteed by Lyapunov's theorem since all eigenvalues of A_cl have negative real parts (verified by pole placement in Â§A.7). V is radially unbounded: V â†’ âˆ as â€–xâ€– â†’ âˆ.

**Step 2 â€” Time derivative.** Computing VÌ‡ along trajectories of the disturbed system:

VÌ‡ = Â½ áº‹áµ€ P x + Â½ xáµ€ P áº‹
   = Â½ (A_cl x + E Ï„_dist)áµ€ P x + Â½ xáµ€ P (A_cl x + E Ï„_dist)
   = Â½ xáµ€ (A_cl^T P + P A_cl) x + xáµ€ P E Ï„_dist
   = âˆ’Â½ xáµ€ Q x + xáµ€ P E Ï„_dist

**Step 3 â€” Bounding the cross term.** By Cauchy-Schwarz and the matrix norm inequality:

|xáµ€ P E Ï„_dist| â‰¤ â€–xâ€– Â· â€–PEâ€– Â· â€–Ï„_distâ€– â‰¤ Î»_max(P) â€–xâ€– Ï„Ì„

(using â€–Eâ€– = 1 since E projects a scalar disturbance onto one state channel per ring, and â€–PEâ€– â‰¤ Î»_max(P)â€–Eâ€– = Î»_max(P))

**Step 4 â€” Completing the bound:**

VÌ‡ â‰¤ âˆ’Â½ Î»_min(Q) â€–xâ€–Â² + Î»_max(P) Ï„Ì„ â€–xâ€–

Factor:

VÌ‡ â‰¤ âˆ’Â½ Î»_min(Q) â€–xâ€– [â€–xâ€– âˆ’ 2Î»_max(P) Ï„Ì„ / Î»_min(Q)]

Define **r* = 2Î»_max(P) Ï„Ì„ / Î»_min(Q)**. Then for all â€–xâ€– > r*:

**VÌ‡ â‰¤ âˆ’Â½ Î»_min(Q)(â€–xâ€– âˆ’ r*) â€–xâ€– < 0** âœ“

**Step 5 â€” UUB conclusion.** Since VÌ‡ < 0 whenever â€–xâ€– > r*, trajectories cannot escape the ball of radius r* indefinitely. By standard UUB arguments (Khalil, Nonlinear Systems, 4th ed., Theorem 4.18), all solutions enter Î© in finite time and remain there for all future time. â–¡

**Numerical bound evaluation:**

With Q = I (identity, simplest choice), the P matrix is obtained from MATLAB's lyap() function:

- Î»_min(Q) = 1.0
- Î»_max(P) â‰ˆ 0.68 (computed for nominal A_cl with gains from Â§A.7)
- Ï„Ì„ = 15 Nm

**r* = 2 Ã— 0.68 Ã— 15 / 1.0 = 20.4** in normalized units

Converting to angular velocity (state units rad/s): r* â‰ˆ **0.018 rad/s** â€” corresponding to a gravity deviation of Î”g = Ï‰Â² r âˆ’ g_des < 0.003 g. Operationally negligible.

