## Appendix B: Superconducting Magnetic Bearing â€” Full Analysis

### B.1 Flux-Pinning Physics

REBCO (rare-earth barium copper oxide) superconductors exhibit the **Meissner effect** and **flux pinning** simultaneously. Below T_c â‰ˆ 93 K, magnetic flux quanta (fluxons, Î¦â‚€ = 2.07 Ã— 10â»Â¹âµ Wb) are trapped at crystallographic defects. Displacement of the superconductor relative to the magnetic source requires energy to move these pinned fluxons â€” generating a restoring force in all six degrees of freedom.

**Force density** from Bean model (critical state):

**f_pin = J_c Ã— B**

where J_c is the critical current density (J_c â‰ˆ 10â¸â€“10â¹ A/mÂ² for REBCO at 40 K, 1 T). For a cylindrical bulk of cross-section A and height h:

**F_pin = J_c B A h / 3** (uniform penetration limit)

For the AMGOH bearing interface (A_eff = 5 mÂ², h = 0.1 m, J_c = 5Ã—10â¸ A/mÂ², B = 0.71 T):

**F_pin = (5Ã—10â¸)(0.71)(5)(0.1)/3 â‰ˆ 5.9 Ã— 10â· N = 59 MN**

This is approximately 100Ã— the required centrifugal load (calculated in Â§4.3 as F_centrifugal â‰ˆ 490 kN for the outer ring). The large safety margin accounts for:
- Temperature-dependent J_c reduction (factor ~3 from 35 K to 77 K)
- Field non-uniformity at bearing gap (factor ~2)
- Fatigue/creep safety factor (3Ã—)

Net available force margin: **~16Ã—** â€” robust by any engineering standard.

### B.2 Thermal Analysis â€” Passive Cooling Verification

The superconducting tapes must remain below T_c = 93 K; nominal design target is 40 K.

**Heat input sources:**
1. Solar irradiance (at 400â€“500 km, 1 AU): Q_sol = Î±_abs Ã— G_sol Ã— A_exposed = 0.05 Ã— 1361 W/mÂ² Ã— A_bearing
2. Earth IR albedo: Q_IR â‰ˆ 0.3 Ã— Q_sol
3. Ohmic dissipation in normal-state regions: Q_ohmic < 1 W/mÂ² (negligible during steady flux-pinning)
4. Structural conduction through ring attachment points: Q_cond â‰ˆ 10 W per interface (MLI-isolated)

**Radiative cooling capacity:** For a deployable black-body radiator panel at temperature T_rad, facing deep space (T_space = 2.7 K):

**Q_rad = Îµ Ïƒ A_rad (T_radâ´ âˆ’ T_spaceâ´) â‰ˆ Îµ Ïƒ A_rad T_radâ´**

Setting T_rad = 45 K (design margin), Îµ = 0.9 (black anodized aluminum):

**Q_rad = 0.9 Ã— 5.67Ã—10â»â¸ Ã— A_rad Ã— (45)â´ = 0.9 Ã— 5.67Ã—10â»â¸ Ã— 4.1Ã—10â¶ Ã— A_rad**
**Q_rad â‰ˆ 0.209 W/mÂ² Ã— A_rad**

Required radiator area to reject total heat load Q_total â‰ˆ 500 W per ring bearing:

**A_rad = 500 / 0.209 â‰ˆ 2,392 mÂ²**

This is approximately **55 m Ã— 43 m** of deployable radiator panels per ring â€” large but consistent with space-heritage deployable radiator technology (ISS radiator arrays are ~892 mÂ² total). AMGOH rings are sufficiently large (r = 9â€“56 m) to accommodate this as a structural double-function surface.

### B.3 Electromagnetic Torque Transfer â€” Induction Coupling Model

Torque is transmitted from the CIC to each ring via **rotating magnetic field induction** â€” analogous to an induction motor with the rotor being the ring and the stator being the CIC-mounted electromagnets.

Torque produced by rotating field at slip frequency Î”Ï‰ = Ï‰_field âˆ’ Ï‰áµ¢:

**Ï„_ind = (3/2) Ã— (Râ‚‚/s) Ã— |Vâ‚|Â² / [(Râ‚ + Râ‚‚/s)Â² + (Xâ‚ + Xâ‚‚)Â²] Ã— (P/Î©_s)**

where s = Î”Ï‰/Ï‰_field is the slip ratio, Râ‚, Râ‚‚ are stator/rotor resistances, Xâ‚, Xâ‚‚ are leakage reactances.

For small slip (fine speed control regime):

**Ï„_ind â‰ˆ (3 |Vâ‚|Â² Râ‚‚) / (s Î©_sÂ² (Râ‚Â² + (Xâ‚+Xâ‚‚)Â²))** Ã— s = **k_Ï„ Î”Ï‰**

This is linear in speed error â€” providing natural proportional torque assistance to the PID law.

Maximum torque (pull-out torque) at s = Râ‚‚/âˆš(Râ‚Â² + X_totalÂ²):

**Ï„_max = (3/2) Ã— |Vâ‚|Â² / [Î©_s (Râ‚ + âˆš(Râ‚Â² + X_totalÂ²))]**

Design target: Ï„_max â‰¥ 1.5 Ã— Ï„_AAMCS,max = 1.5 Ã— 15 Nm Ã— (Iâ‚ƒ/I_ref) â‰ˆ **1.2 Ã— 10â¶ Nm** for outer ring.

