### E.2 Marginal Revenue of Gravity

Revenue per hour of gravity service at level gáµ¢:

**R(gáµ¢) = P_GaaS(gáµ¢) Ã— T_service**

From the MUG table, market premium per unit quality:

For ZBLAN (Micro-G tier): P_product â‰ˆ $3M/kg, production rate Ï† â‰ˆ 0.1 kg/hr

**Revenue rate = QM(g) Ã— P_product Ã— Ï† = 50 Ã— $3M Ã— 0.1 = $15M/hr** at 0.02 g

**âˆ‚R/âˆ‚g = d[QM(g) Ã— P_product Ã— Ï†]/dg = P_product Ã— Ï† Ã— dQM/dg**

**dQM/dg = âˆ’Î¦ Ã— QM(g)** (from exponential yield function)

At g = 0.02 g_E: **dQM/dg = âˆ’10 Ã— 50 = âˆ’500 g_Eâ»Â¹**

**âˆ‚R/âˆ‚g = $3M Ã— 0.1 Ã— (âˆ’500) = âˆ’$150M / g_E per hour**

(Negative because lower g = higher yield â€” revenue increases as g decreases from 1.)

**Equilibrium condition:** |âˆ‚R/âˆ‚g| â‰« âˆ‚C/âˆ‚g:

**$150,000,000 â‰« $454** per gÂ·hr âœ“ â€” by a factor of **330,000Ã—**

This enormous margin is what makes orbital manufacturing of high-value Micro-G products economically overwhelming. Even accounting for capital costs amortized over the habitat lifetime, the economic equilibrium holds with enormous headroom.

